07243nam a22007815i 9781787446175DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874461757 a10.1515/97817874461752doi  a(DE-B1597)676764  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a398.35200aArthurian Literature XXXV /ced. by David F. Johnson, Elizabeth Archibald.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2020] 1bD.S.Brewer, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (227 p.) :b5 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArthurian Literature ;v3500tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tGENERAL EDITORS’ FOREWORD -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tI ARTHURIAN SWORDS I: GAWAIN’S SWORD AND THE LEGEND OF WELAND THE SMITH -- tII REX REBELLIS ET VIR PACIFICUS: CIVIL WAR AND ECCLESIASTICAL PEACEKEEPING IN THE VITA GILDAE OF CARADOG OF LLANCARFAN -- tIII ONCE AND FUTURE HISTORY: TEXTUAL BORROWING IN AN ACCOUNT OF THE FIRST WAR OF SCOTTISH INDEPENDENCE -- tIV ‘ME REWES SORE’: WOMEN’S FRIENDSHIP, AFFECT AND LOYALTY IN YWAIN AND GAWAIN -- tV THE SACRED AND THE SECULAR: ALCHEMICAL TRANSFORMATION IN THE TURKE AND SIR GAWAIN -- tVI ‘THE NATIVE PLACE OF THAT GREAT ARTHUR’: FOREIGNNESS AND NATIVITY IN SIXTEENTHCENTURY DEFENCES OF ARTHUR -- tVII JOHN STEINBECK’S ‘WONDER-WORDS’ -- tVIII THE ONCE AND FUTURE KING OF ATLANTIS: THE ARTHURIAN FIGURE IN GEOFF JOHNS’S AQUAMAN: DEATH OF A KING -- tIX ARTHUR AND/OR THE GRAIL0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe continued influence and significance of the legend of Arthur are demonstrated by the articles collected in this volume.The rich vitality of both the Arthurian material itself and the scholarship devoted to it is manifested in this volume. It begins with an interdisciplinary study of swords belonging to Arthurian and other heroes and of the smithswho made them, assessed both in their literary contexts and in "historical" references to their existence as heroic relics. Two essays then consider the use of Arthurian material for political purposes: a discussion of Caradog's Vita Gildae throws light on the complex attitudes to Arthur of contemporaries of Geoffrey of Monmouth in a time of political turmoil in England, and an investigation into borrowings from Geoffrey's Historia in a chronicle of Anglo-Scottish relations in the time of Edward I, a well-known admirer of the Arthurian legend, argues that they would have appealed to the clerical élite. Romance motifs link the subsequent pieces: women and their friendships in Ywain and Gawain, the only known close English adaptation of a romance by Chrétien, and the mixture of sacred and secular in The Turke and Gawain, with fascinating alchemical parallels for a puzzling beheading episode. This is followed by a discussion of the views on native and foreign sources of three sixteenth-century defenders of Arthur, John Leland, John Prise and Humphrey Llwyd, and their responses to the criticisms of Polydore Vergil. In twentieth-century reception history, John Steinbeck was an ardent Arthurian enthusiast: an essay looks at the significance of his annotations to his copy of Malory as he worked on his adaptation, The Acts of King Arthur and his Noble Knights. The volume moves to even more recent territory with an exploration of the adaptations of Malory and other Arthurian writers that occur in the comic books by Geoff Johns about Arthur Curry, aka Aquaman, King of Atlantis. The book is completed by a reprint of a classic essay by Norris Lacy on the absence and presence of the Grail in Arthurian texts from the twelfth century on. ELIZABETH ARCHIBALD is Professor of English Studies at Durham University, and Principal of St Cuthbert's Society; DAVID F. JOHNSON is Professor of English at Florida State University, Tallahassee. Contributors: Richard Barber, Mary Bateman, Christopher Berard, William J. Fowler, Natalie Goodison, Norris Lacy, Andrew Rabin, Carl Sell, Elaine Treharne, Usha Vishnuvajjala  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romances. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aComic.  aHoly Grail.  afrench romance.  agraphc novel.1 aArchibald, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArchibald, Elizabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarber, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBateman, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerard, Christopher Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerard, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodison, Natalie Jayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodison, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, David F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, David F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLacy, Norris J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacy, Norris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabin, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSell, Carl B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSell, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreharne, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVishnuvajjala, Usha, econtri